    <h2>Best Zones for Birdwatching</h2>

    <h3>Sarhi Zone — Premier Birding Destination</h3>
    <p>
      Sarhi Zone is the least-visited of Kanha's four zones, accessed via Sarhi Gate (30 km east of Khatia).
      The zone offers quiet trails, dense forest, and minimal visitor disturbance — ideal for birdwatching.
      Species commonly seen include Brown Fish Owl, various woodpeckers, forest flycatchers, and secretive
      species often missed in busier zones.
    </p>

    <h3>Kisli Zone — Forest Birding</h3>
    <p>
      Kisli Zone's mature Sal forests and waterhole edges support exceptional forest bird diversity. Early
      morning drives through Kisli typically produce 40-60 species. The zone is accessed via Khatia Gate.
    </p>

    <h3>Kanha Zone — Meadow and Edge Species</h3>
    <p>
      Kanha Zone meadows attract ground-dwelling species like Indian Peafowl, Red Junglefowl, Painted Spurfowl,
      and various pipits. Forest edges harbor mixed-species feeding flocks with warblers, flycatchers, and
      babblers.
    </p>

    <h2>Best Time for Birdwatching</h2>

    <table>
      <thead>
        <tr><th>Season</th><th>Months</th><th>Bird Activity</th><th>Recommendation</th></tr>
      </thead>
      <tbody>
        <tr><td>Winter</td><td>Nov-Feb</td><td>Peak season with migrants</td><td>Best overall</td></tr>
        <tr><td>Summer</td><td>Mar-May</td><td>Residents, breeding plumage</td><td>Good for residents</td></tr>
        <tr><td>Post-monsoon</td><td>Oct</td><td>Residents active, returning migrants</td><td>Good for photography</td></tr>
        <tr><td>Monsoon</td><td>Jul-Sep</td><td>Park closed</td><td>Not applicable</td></tr>
      </tbody>
    </table>

    <h3>Winter Migrants at Kanha</h3>
    <p>
      Kanha's winter (November-February) brings several notable migrants from the Himalayas and Central Asia:
    </p>

    <ul>
      <li>Indian Pitta</li>
      <li>Verditer Flycatcher</li>
      <li>Red-breasted Flycatcher</li>
      <li>Taiga Flycatcher</li>
      <li>Black Redstart</li>
      <li>Forest Wagtail</li>
      <li>Common Rosefinch</li>
      <li>Oriental Honey Buzzard</li>
      <li>Steppe Eagle</li>
    </ul>

    <h2>Birdwatching Tips at Kanha</h2>

    <ol>
      <li><strong>Early morning is best:</strong> 6:00-9:00 AM peak activity</li>
      <li><strong>Stay quiet:</strong> Move slowly, avoid sudden movements</li>
      <li><strong>Listen for calls:</strong> Birds often heard before seen</li>
      <li><strong>Use binoculars:</strong> 8x42 or 10x42 ideal for forest viewing</li>
      <li><strong>Hire local guides:</strong> Naturalists know seasonal hotspots</li>
      <li><strong>Visit waterholes:</strong> Concentrated bird activity at water sources</li>
      <li><strong>Check mixed flocks:</strong> Forest flocks often contain multiple species</li>
    </ol>

    <h2>Endemic and Rare Species</h2>

    <p>
      While Kanha doesn't host species found nowhere else, it supports several species of conservation concern:
    </p>

    <ul>
      <li><strong>Indian Vulture:</strong> Critically endangered, occasionally seen</li>
      <li><strong>Forest Owlet:</strong> Critically endangered, rediscovered in central India</li>
      <li><strong>Indian Skimmer:</strong> Endangered, rarely seen at water bodies</li>
      <li><strong>Lesser Florican:</strong> Endangered, very rare</li>
    </ul>

    <FAQ faqs={faqs} />

        <Testimonials />

        <AuthorBox />
      <ResourcesHub />

      <RelatedPages pages={relatedPages} />

        </div>

      <div class="lg:col-span-1">
        <div class="sticky top-32">
          <Sidebar currentPath={Astro.url.pathname} />
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>

    <RelatedPages pages={relatedPages} />

  </main>

  <Footer />
</BaseLayout>
